Agriculture was not &quot;well developed&quot; in North America outside the area controlled by the Aztecs (I confused the Aztecs, Incas and Mayans, so if I use the wrong one, I apologize. I believe th Aztecs were the only truly agrarian society in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> North</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> America.)<br>
<br>
What particular crops they may have grown is not as significant as the methods by which they grew them. A victory garden in my backyard does not suddenly make me the equivalent of a commercial farmer. I did say that the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> vast majority</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> were hunter-gatherers. Whereas the Europeans of the period had entered the industrial stage, the Americans had barely entered the agrarian stage, with the Aztecs, Incans and Mayans being the farthest developed. None of them ruled over even a major portion of the continents.<br>
<br>
At the time of the discovery of N. America, the Mayan, Incan and Aztec cultures were already beginning to decay. The suggestion that a few hundred or even a few thousand Conquistadors could destroy a civilization that, by your reckoning, must have numbered in the millions is absurd.<br>
As for predisposition to alcoholism and lack of disease resistance... hallucinagenic and other drugs had been available in the Americas long before alcohol made its way here. As for disease... a century before Columbus discovered the Americas (whether anyone else had previously discovered them is irrelevant; Columbus had never seen them before, so in this context it's adequate to say he &quot;discovered&quot; them,) western Europe was ravaged by the black death, bubonic and pneumonic plague. A disease not native to western Europe but brought there from the orient. There was virtually no sanitation, what medical treatment there was was most often worse than the cure. The disease killed 2/3s of the western European population... yet a century later they had rebounded, and were expanding. It's curious that the Americans, facing much the same situation (with a much smaller focus of infection, and a time period of isolation from further infection) would be so terribly ravaged simply because the diseases they encountered was alien to them. Later, it was a practice among some unscrupulous European-Amerians, to give blankets that had been used by smallpox sufferers to the then-native Americans, in an effort to spread disease and kill them. But that was centuries later.<br>
<br>
I suggest the cause of the alcoholism was cultural emasculation, so to speak. The apparent superiority of European culture (guns, steel weapons, etc) combined with the self-assurance and aggressiveness of most of the European invaders, in my opinion, caused the Americans to lose faith in themselves and their various cultures. Not all of them, and not suddenly, of course. Much the same would happen to the world if space aliens were to land tomorrow with ray guns and teleporter beams and what-have-you. We might survive better because we know that it's merely advanced science, but one cannot underestimate the effect of morale, for good or bad.<br>
Interesting that you should mention war as a cause of the death of Americans, because it's often overlooked that the various tribes of N. America did not play well together, to begin with. <br>
<br>
As for seeking help, alright, I'll call 911... what's your address, so I know where to send the ambulance?<br>
 <p>Aldrin of the Nexus<BR>
